Its discovery was officially recognized by the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry and the International Union of Pure and Applied Physics in 2016. The element is named after the state of Tennessee in the United States of America, recognizing the contributions of the Oak Ridge National Laboratory and Vanderbilt University to superheavy element research.

Moscovium, with atomic number 115, was first synthesized in 2003 by a joint Russian-American collaboration at the Joint Institute for Nuclear Research in Dubna, Russia. Its discovery was officially recognized in 2016. The element is named after the Moscow Oblast region in Russia, where the Joint Institute for Nuclear Research is located.

Nihonium, with atomic number 113, was first synthesized in 2003 by a team at RIKEN in Wako, Japan. Its discovery was officially recognized in 2016. It is the first element on the periodic table to be discovered in an Asian country. The element is named after "Nihon," one of the two Japanese names for Japan, meaning "the land of the rising sun."

Oganesson, with atomic number 118, was first synthesized in 2002 by a joint Russian-American collaboration at the Joint Institute for Nuclear Research in Dubna, Russia. Its discovery was confirmed in 2006 and officially recognized in 2016. It is named after Yuri Oganessian, a prominent Russian nuclear physicist who has made significant contributions to the discovery of superheavy elements. Oganesson is currently the heaviest element on the periodic table.

Livermorium, with atomic number 116, was first synthesized in 2000 by a joint Russian-American collaboration at the Joint Institute for Nuclear Research in Dubna, Russia, and the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory in the United States of America. Its discovery was officially recognized in 2016. The element is named after the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory in California, United States of America, which played a crucial role in its discovery.
